I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to view them critically.
We grew up in an age of media abundance, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could jump into things without having to wonder where they came from, because it wasn't so easy to figure that out back then.
We didn't have to question the platform we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
As "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the show together.
This was very different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches whenever they want and posts on social media with spoiler warnings or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
This is why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman", which had so many one-liners that would now be memes.
We knew all these jokes and assumed that most people understood them.
Heute kann man zelfständig nicht davon ausgehen, dass jeder etwas kennt, selbst wenn es sich massiv viral verbreitet.
Es gibt viel zu viel, und es gibt keine Möglichkeit, es zu systematisieren. Ob wir überhaupt wieder aus dieser Übersättigung rauskommen?
Wir sind in einem Teufelskreis gefangen, immer wieder neue Inhalte zu entdecken, nur um dann zu merken, dass der Künstler geldgierig oder ein Heuchler ist.
Deshalb müssen wir uns an unserer Nostalgie festhalten und gleichzeitig akzeptieren, dass die Leute, die die Werke geschaffen haben, die uns gefallen haben, auch große Fehler haben können.
Wir gehen parasoziale Beziehungen mit größerer Vorsicht ein.
It is clear that it is hard to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes on the way there.
Since our collective consciousness regarding media has faded, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters critical thinking.
There are still those among us who elevate someone to a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
We are in a phase of transition and I am curious to see where it will all lead in the end.
